y of emotions and life-cycle history, Christian Bailey moves beyond existing research into the sexual and racial politics of modern Germany and approaches a new frontier in the study of subjectivity and the self. German Jews in Love draws on a rich array of sources, from newspapers and love letters to state and other official records. Calling on this evidence, Bailey shows the ways German Jews' romantic relationships reveal an aspect of acculturation that has been overlooked: how deeply cultural scripts worked their way into emotions; those most intimate and seemingly pre-political aspects of German-Jewish subjectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aIntermarriagezGermanyxHistory. 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszGermanyxIdentityxHistory. 0aLovezGermanyxHistory. 0aMan-woman relationshipszGermanyxHistory. 0aMarriagezGermanyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aacculturation.  aemotional script.  aemotions.  agender.  alove myth.  alove.  amodernity.  aself.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363416940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503634169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503634169/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles